Google has never
won a World Series.

00:39:19.450 --> 00:39:20.030
KEITH LAW: No, no.

00:39:20.030 --> 00:39:20.720
AUDIENCE: It's amazing.

00:39:20.720 --> 00:39:21.830
KEITH LAW: Neither
has Houston, though.

00:39:21.830 --> 00:39:23.015
So you're equal, right?

00:39:23.015 --> 00:39:23.681
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:39:23.681 --> 00:39:24.250
Right.

00:39:24.250 --> 00:39:25.460
And by the way, you're
absolutely right.

00:39:25.460 --> 00:39:26.918
Like, a lot of his
first hires have

00:39:26.918 --> 00:39:29.000
been software engineers
to just process the data,

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:30.440
as well as QAs.

00:39:30.440 --> 00:39:32.990
So in the spirit
of the Statcast,

00:39:32.990 --> 00:39:35.210
we were just talking
about, my question,

00:39:35.210 --> 00:39:37.760
which is somewhat like interview
questions we ask here is,

00:39:37.760 --> 00:39:39.680
suppose you could have
any data collected

00:39:39.680 --> 00:39:40.730
to answer any question.

00:39:40.730 --> 00:39:43.579
So after Statcast,
what data do you

00:39:43.579 --> 00:39:44.870
want to start seeing collected?

00:39:44.870 --> 00:39:48.670
Is it off the field health data?

00:39:48.670 --> 00:39:51.330
Suppose we mine Statcast
in the next five, 10 years,

00:39:51.330 --> 00:39:53.330
and learn defense, and
learn all this stuff

00:39:53.330 --> 00:39:54.320
you just talked about.

00:39:54.320 --> 00:39:56.870
What data do you
want to collect next?

00:39:56.870 --> 00:39:58.820
KEITH LAW: There's two answers.

00:39:58.820 --> 00:40:01.280
And we're starting to do the
TrackMan portion of Statcast

00:40:01.280 --> 00:40:02.212
data.

00:40:02.212 --> 00:40:04.670
We're starting to get some more
of that on amateur players.

00:40:04.670 --> 00:40:08.214
Certainly, so in 10 days from
now, I'll be at Wrigley Field

00:40:08.214 --> 00:40:10.130
for the Under Armour
All-American Class, which

00:40:10.130 --> 00:40:13.730
is kind of an all-star game
of high school rising seniors

00:40:13.730 --> 00:40:14.837
for next year's draft.

00:40:14.837 --> 00:40:16.670
The Cubs just turned
the TrackMan system on,

00:40:16.670 --> 00:40:18.830
and they can collect
data from that game

00:40:18.830 --> 00:40:20.510
on all of those players.

00:40:20.510 --> 00:40:23.870
And evaluating
high school players

00:40:23.870 --> 00:40:25.490
has always been
entirely subjective.

00:40:25.490 --> 00:40:27.110
There has just been no data
because high school stats

00:40:27.110 --> 00:40:27.450
great.

00:40:27.450 --> 00:40:28.070
You hit .600.

00:40:28.070 --> 00:40:30.040
That's really not
useful to me at all.

00:40:30.040 --> 00:40:30.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:30.540 --> 00:40:32.290
AUDIENCE: I hit
.600 in high school.

00:40:32.290 --> 00:40:34.810
KEITH LAW: Or yes, he struck
out two guys an inning.

00:40:34.810 --> 00:40:35.810
He throws 95.

00:40:35.810 --> 00:40:38.240
And no one else in the
county throws more than 70.

00:40:38.240 --> 00:40:40.010
So again, not very useful.

00:40:40.010 --> 00:40:42.500
But having TrackMan
data at least help us,

00:40:42.500 --> 00:40:46.400
even if it's just putting those
amateur players into buckets

00:40:46.400 --> 00:40:49.570
to help us give another
objective component,

00:40:49.570 --> 00:40:51.320
or to help us compare
high school players

00:40:51.320 --> 00:40:53.450
to college players,
which was a problem when

00:40:53.450 --> 00:40:54.080
I was with the Blue Jays.

00:40:54.080 --> 00:40:55.788
I think it's still a
problem figuring out

00:40:55.788 --> 00:40:56.950
how to value those guys.

00:40:56.950 --> 00:40:59.180
So we're heading in that
direction, certainly.

00:40:59.180 --> 00:41:01.641
The cost of the system
is a little prohibitive.

00:41:01.641 --> 00:41:03.140
But they're putting
TrackMan systems

00:41:03.140 --> 00:41:05.540
in a lot of minor
league parks to which,

00:41:05.540 --> 00:41:08.670
if you're running a
minor league park, hey,

00:41:08.670 --> 00:41:10.160
let's do a local
high school event.

00:41:10.160 --> 00:41:11.618
Just flick the
system, and then you

00:41:11.618 --> 00:41:14.120
can turn around and sell
the data to the teams too.

00:41:14.120 --> 00:41:16.340
The other thing,
and I think it's

00:41:16.340 --> 00:41:18.860
coming but it might be a
few years down the road,

00:41:18.860 --> 00:41:19.887
is more biometric data.

00:41:19.887 --> 00:41:21.470
And there are people
trying to invent,

00:41:21.470 --> 00:41:22.910
like, the Motus sleeve is one.

00:41:22.910 --> 00:41:25.460
I don't know if it actually
does what it's claiming to do,

00:41:25.460 --> 00:41:26.667
but I love the idea.

00:41:26.667 --> 00:41:29.000
It's a sleeve that pitchers
would wear and then actually

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:29.510
pitch--

00:41:29.510 --> 00:41:32.270
whether it's in games or merely
just doing side sessions--

00:41:32.270 --> 00:41:34.820
that would track
things like stress

00:41:34.820 --> 00:41:36.380
on certain parts of the joint.

00:41:36.380 --> 00:41:39.260
Like the valgus force on the
elbow, which is possibly,

00:41:39.260 --> 00:41:42.620
probably, one of the
potential causes of UCL tears.

00:41:42.620 --> 00:41:45.170
Even more so on the shoulder,
which, once the shoulder goes,

00:41:45.170 --> 00:41:47.660
it's a lot harder to
fix than a torn elbow

00:41:47.660 --> 00:41:50.600
ligament, which Tommy John,
80%, 85% success rate.

00:41:50.600 --> 00:41:52.730
Shoulder surgery success
rate's a lot lower.

00:41:52.730 --> 00:41:57.025
If we could identify things in
the shoulder, signs of fatigue.

00:41:57.025 --> 00:41:58.400
You know, what I
talked about was

00:41:58.400 --> 00:42:00.524
second order, this idea
that spin rate is dropping.

00:42:00.524 --> 00:42:04.430
What if we could see changes
in the shoulder sooner,

00:42:04.430 --> 00:42:06.680
or knees, lower back?

00:42:06.680 --> 00:42:08.600
I mean, baseball
players get hurt

00:42:08.600 --> 00:42:10.470
a lot for a non-contact sport.

00:42:10.470 --> 00:42:11.670
AUDIENCE: A lot of these
are cascades, right?

00:42:11.670 --> 00:42:12.325
KEITH LAW: Yes.

00:42:12.325 --> 00:42:13.880
AUDIENCE: It starts in a leg,
and it turns into a shoulder.

00:42:13.880 --> 00:42:15.296
KEITH LAW: This
is always my fear,

00:42:15.296 --> 00:42:18.226
and I feel pretty
confident I've seen

00:42:18.226 --> 00:42:19.850
it happen with pitchers
over the years,

00:42:19.850 --> 00:42:20.900
too, that something goes wrong.

00:42:20.900 --> 00:42:21.816
A little ankle injury.

00:42:21.816 --> 00:42:23.533
Well I want to pitch through it.

00:42:23.533 --> 00:42:24.740
I'm gonna change the
delivery slightly.

00:42:24.740 --> 00:42:25.740
Next thing you know,
it's the elbow.

00:42:25.740 --> 00:42:26.780
It's the shoulder.

00:42:26.780 --> 00:42:29.734
Anything we can do to just
spot it before it happens.

00:42:29.734 --> 00:42:32.150
Players are always going to
get hurt, especially pitchers.

00:42:32.150 --> 00:42:35.930
But if we can stop it before it
gets too far, like I was just

00:42:35.930 --> 00:42:38.090
saying earlier, that's a
huge financial savings.

00:42:38.090 --> 00:42:40.310
And I think it makes
it a better product.

00:42:40.310 --> 00:42:42.070
We want the better
players on the field.

00:42:42.070 --> 00:42:44.900
And I hate everything-- sort
of a running gag on Twitter--

00:42:44.900 --> 00:42:48.470
every time a pitcher blows out,
it's also an acknowledgement

00:42:48.470 --> 00:42:50.150
that this is just
part of the sport.

00:42:50.150 --> 00:42:53.327
If we could reduce that
sooner using data--

00:42:53.327 --> 00:42:55.160
it's not like we found
another way to do it.

00:42:55.160 --> 00:42:58.146
Data is kind of like our last
best hope to try to do that.

00:42:58.146 --> 00:42:59.754
AUDIENCE: I have two questions.

00:42:59.754 --> 00:43:01.670
The first one is, how
much [? stat ?] activity

00:43:01.670 --> 00:43:05.540
do you still see in
the front office based

00:43:05.540 --> 00:43:08.540
on, say, the race, or the
height, or the outfit,

00:43:08.540 --> 00:43:10.100
or the background
for the players,

00:43:10.100 --> 00:43:13.337
despite having the data
[INAUDIBLE] in the past decade?

00:43:13.337 --> 00:43:14.420
That's the first question.

00:43:14.420 --> 00:43:14.830
KEITH LAW: Go ahead.

00:43:14.830 --> 00:43:16.204
AUDIENCE: And the
second question

00:43:16.204 --> 00:43:20.600
is, how much data
do voters nowadays

00:43:20.600 --> 00:43:23.390
use to vote for MVPs
or Hall of Famers?

00:43:23.390 --> 00:43:25.910
Do they still use their
subjective observations?

00:43:25.910 --> 00:43:28.520
KEITH LAW: So to the first
question, it's changed.

00:43:31.670 --> 00:43:34.100
I'm sure there's still
racism within baseball,

00:43:34.100 --> 00:43:36.530
as there is everywhere in
the industry, everywhere

00:43:36.530 --> 00:43:37.710
in society.

00:43:37.710 --> 00:43:39.710
I think it's gotten
a lot better.

00:43:39.710 --> 00:43:42.530
And I think that the
change in the composition

00:43:42.530 --> 00:43:44.120
of the front
offices where you've

00:43:44.120 --> 00:43:46.369
got more of a mix of people
from different backgrounds

00:43:46.369 --> 00:43:48.536
too means that that kind
of thinking, if it pops up,

00:43:48.536 --> 00:43:50.618
it's just going to kind
of be dismissed or swatted

00:43:50.618 --> 00:43:51.500
away a little sooner.

00:43:51.500 --> 00:43:53.000
You mentioned height.

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:58.010
That, to me, is one that is
probably still overconsidered,

00:43:58.010 --> 00:43:59.180
especially for hitters.

00:43:59.180 --> 00:44:03.540
Like, we've seen Andrew
Benintendi, Alex Bregman,

00:44:03.540 --> 00:44:05.040
they're all listed
at, like, 6 foot.

00:44:05.040 --> 00:44:08.030
If they're 6 foot, I'm 5' 11".

00:44:08.030 --> 00:44:10.011
I mean, I've met
Alex Bregman twice.

00:44:10.011 --> 00:44:11.260
And I can look him in the eye.

00:44:11.260 --> 00:44:12.509
It's like, dude, you're 5' 8".

00:44:12.509 --> 00:44:14.420
Marcus Stroman is
probably 5' 8".

00:44:14.420 --> 00:44:15.730
He might be 5' 9".

00:44:15.730 --> 00:44:17.300
But these guys are pretty good.

00:44:17.300 --> 00:44:20.450
But there's still a fairly
strong bias against players

00:44:20.450 --> 00:44:23.870
who are undersized like that.

00:44:23.870 --> 00:44:27.891
To me, we're still working
to create some separation

00:44:27.891 --> 00:44:29.390
because I do think
there are aspects

00:44:29.390 --> 00:44:33.050
where height, especially for a
pitcher, might really matter.

00:44:33.050 --> 00:44:38.305
You know, if you are a
pitcher, especially if you're

00:44:38.305 --> 00:44:40.680
throwing a four seamer, and
you're not particularly tall,

00:44:40.680 --> 00:44:42.500
and that fastball is
coming in fairly flat,

00:44:42.500 --> 00:44:44.150
you're going to give up
a lot of air contact.

00:44:44.150 --> 00:44:46.340
You may just be giving
up harder contact period.

00:44:46.340 --> 00:44:46.970
That's real.

00:44:46.970 --> 00:44:49.880
That's a real effect that we
might be able to measure better

00:44:49.880 --> 00:44:51.484
going forward, too.

00:44:51.484 --> 00:44:53.150
There's also this
longstanding mentality

00:44:53.150 --> 00:44:55.400
that short pitchers
get hurt more often.

00:44:55.400 --> 00:44:57.765
I've never seen any
evidence to back that up,

00:44:57.765 --> 00:44:59.390
and it still kills
me when I hear that.

00:44:59.390 --> 00:45:01.870
We see tall pitchers
get hurt all the time.

00:45:01.870 --> 00:45:04.370
And then, there's a corollary
that really tall pitchers also

00:45:04.370 --> 00:45:07.400
get hurt more often because
they can't coordinate.

00:45:07.400 --> 00:45:08.650
They can't all be 6' 2".

00:45:08.650 --> 00:45:09.230
I'm sorry.

00:45:09.230 --> 00:45:11.420
Like, we're not putting
them out of a factory here.

00:45:11.420 --> 00:45:13.790
You're gonna have to
figure out what the--

00:45:13.790 --> 00:45:14.480
first of all,
you're going to have

00:45:14.480 --> 00:45:16.250
to prove either of those
assertions, which I don't think

00:45:16.250 --> 00:45:16.750
are true.

00:45:16.750 --> 00:45:19.130
And second is figure out what's
your comfort level if you

00:45:19.130 --> 00:45:20.921
really do think a
shorter or taller pitcher

00:45:20.921 --> 00:45:23.300
is going to get hurt.

00:45:23.300 --> 00:45:27.230
To your second question,
using more data,

00:45:27.230 --> 00:45:30.860
better data has shown up
more in annual award voting

00:45:30.860 --> 00:45:32.919
because that electorate
changes constantly.

00:45:32.919 --> 00:45:34.460
You have to be an
active writer to be

00:45:34.460 --> 00:45:35.960
able to vote on those awards.

00:45:35.960 --> 00:45:38.760
The Hall of Fame, though,
they did change it.

00:45:38.760 --> 00:45:40.370
They got rid of some
of the dinosaurs

00:45:40.370 --> 00:45:41.540
recently with a rule change.

00:45:41.540 --> 00:45:44.120
But still, there are people
who have not covered baseball

00:45:44.120 --> 00:45:47.330
for eight or nine years who
still have Hall of Fame votes.

00:45:47.330 --> 00:45:48.950
You get a vote.

00:45:48.950 --> 00:45:50.090
It used to be lifetime.

00:45:50.090 --> 00:45:52.400
Once you spent 10
consecutive years

00:45:52.400 --> 00:45:55.520
as an active badge holder, which
I am a member of the Baseball

00:45:55.520 --> 00:45:56.430
Writers' Association.

00:45:56.430 --> 00:45:59.630
And then, once you got the vote,
it was yours till you died.

00:45:59.630 --> 00:46:02.690
Now you get it, and you hold
it as long as you're active,

00:46:02.690 --> 00:46:05.480
plus 10 years when you
stop covering baseball,

00:46:05.480 --> 00:46:06.152
10 years beyond.

00:46:06.152 --> 00:46:08.360
So we've still got a lot of
guys who have just missed

00:46:08.360 --> 00:46:09.920
the analytics revolution.

00:46:09.920 --> 00:46:10.801
Don't care.

00:46:10.801 --> 00:46:12.050
I mentioned some names before.

00:46:12.050 --> 00:46:13.490
Guys who just don't
agree with it.

00:46:13.490 --> 00:46:14.840
They still have votes.

00:46:14.840 --> 00:46:17.540
Whereas they may not be voting
on annual awards anymore.

00:46:17.540 --> 00:46:19.040
And so it's going
to take more time.

00:46:19.040 --> 00:46:21.991
Sort of the Max Planck thing
on science, when science really

00:46:21.991 --> 00:46:22.490
changes.

00:46:22.490 --> 00:46:24.420
It's not that one side
convinces the other,

00:46:24.420 --> 00:46:26.000
it's that the other side dies.

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:28.320
And that's when the new
idea manages to win.

00:46:28.320 --> 00:46:30.778
I mean, that's kind of what's
happening in the Hall of Fame

00:46:30.778 --> 00:46:32.900
voting too is the older
anti-analytics people

00:46:32.900 --> 00:46:35.800
are just gradually going to
stop voting because they passed

00:46:35.800 --> 00:46:37.250
away, or they just
get old enough

00:46:37.250 --> 00:46:40.310
and they don't vote
anymore, or they age out.

00:46:40.310 --> 00:46:45.120
And 10 years from now, I think
it's going to be much more--

00:46:45.120 --> 00:46:46.611
I don't want to say data driven.

00:46:46.611 --> 00:46:47.610
It's going to be better.

00:46:47.610 --> 00:46:48.410
We're going to get
better results.

00:46:48.410 --> 00:46:50.660
We're going to get more
fact-based voting, which

00:46:50.660 --> 00:46:51.370
is all I ask for.

00:46:51.370 --> 00:46:53.120
We don't all have to
agree on the players,

00:46:53.120 --> 00:46:54.980
but I would like it to be
more grounded in reality, not

00:46:54.980 --> 00:46:56.630
on whether Jim Rice
was really feared.

00:46:59.920 --> 00:47:01.646
AUDIENCE: I have a
question about how

00:47:01.646 --> 00:47:03.770
some of these advanced
metrics and the availability

00:47:03.770 --> 00:47:05.989
of information might
affect the umpiring.

00:47:05.989 --> 00:47:07.530
So we talk a lot
about pitch framing.

00:47:07.530 --> 00:47:09.710
And you see catchers that are
really good at it or bad at it.

00:47:09.710 --> 00:47:11.376
Do you think that,
eventually, that this

00:47:11.376 --> 00:47:13.760
could lead to either front
offices or even people

00:47:13.760 --> 00:47:16.130
in the media pushing for a
different type of umpire?

00:47:16.130 --> 00:47:18.290
I mean, I read in Brian Kenny's
book that, back in the day,

00:47:18.290 --> 00:47:19.720
the umpires had to
be big and strong

00:47:19.720 --> 00:47:22.040
and potentially break up
actual physical altercations.

00:47:22.040 --> 00:47:24.535
And that clearly
has still bled over

00:47:24.535 --> 00:47:26.410
to the type of umpires
that are around today.

00:47:26.410 --> 00:47:28.250
You get a lot of them that
you talk about your ump shows

00:47:28.250 --> 00:47:28.840
on Twitter.

00:47:28.840 --> 00:47:30.710
And you see people that
love to insert themselves

00:47:30.710 --> 00:47:31.793
in the middle of the game.

00:47:31.793 --> 00:47:34.450
Do you see the profile of
an umpire changing over time

00:47:34.450 --> 00:47:36.200
as a result of this
available information?

00:47:36.200 --> 00:47:37.280
KEITH LAW: I haven't.

00:47:37.280 --> 00:47:39.980
I don't think so.

00:47:39.980 --> 00:47:42.200
My one hesitation is
Major League Baseball

00:47:42.200 --> 00:47:43.730
does have more
umpire accountability

00:47:43.730 --> 00:47:45.140
behind the scenes than we see.

00:47:45.140 --> 00:47:47.030
Umpires are evaluated
on things like

00:47:47.030 --> 00:47:49.190
their ball-strike accuracy.

00:47:49.190 --> 00:47:51.350
They don't release any
of that to the public.

00:47:51.350 --> 00:47:53.516
I wish they were a little
more transparent about it,

00:47:53.516 --> 00:47:54.650
certainly.

00:47:54.650 --> 00:47:58.875
And I don't really understand
the idea why they're not.

00:47:58.875 --> 00:48:01.250
I think-- and I've expressed
this to some people at Major

00:48:01.250 --> 00:48:03.262
League Baseball too--

00:48:03.262 --> 00:48:05.720
these guys are more accurate
than the average fan, I think,

00:48:05.720 --> 00:48:06.886
gives them credit for being.

00:48:06.886 --> 00:48:08.570
Rob Manfred even
said yesterday he

00:48:08.570 --> 00:48:11.390
thought if we went to
automated ball-strike calling,

00:48:11.390 --> 00:48:14.360
we'd have a larger margin
of error, I think he said,

00:48:14.360 --> 00:48:16.790
with the technology
than we do with people.

00:48:16.790 --> 00:48:17.810
That may be true.

00:48:17.810 --> 00:48:19.518
If you actually invest
in the technology,

00:48:19.518 --> 00:48:22.100
it's probably going
to shrink over time.

00:48:22.100 --> 00:48:24.530
I've also argued too, I think
you'll get more consistency.

00:48:24.530 --> 00:48:27.200
I think batters and
pitchers would say,

00:48:27.200 --> 00:48:31.497
we're fine if we don't actually
improve the accuracy right now.

00:48:31.497 --> 00:48:32.455
We want predictability.

00:48:32.455 --> 00:48:33.404
We want consistency.

00:48:33.404 --> 00:48:34.820
I want to know
that that ball that

00:48:34.820 --> 00:48:38.540
is 2 inches from the
edge of the plate

00:48:38.540 --> 00:48:41.540
is always going to
be called a strike.

00:48:41.540 --> 00:48:45.257
But I think Major League
Baseball would do pretty well

00:48:45.257 --> 00:48:46.715
to release more of
that information

00:48:46.715 --> 00:48:48.650
and show us that, hey,
some of these umpires

00:48:48.650 --> 00:48:50.750
are actually more
accurate than you think.

00:48:50.750 --> 00:48:53.300
I don't get the sense
that they've necessarily

00:48:53.300 --> 00:48:55.460
changed the type of people
they're looking for.

00:48:55.460 --> 00:48:57.470
And I know people at
Major League Baseball

00:48:57.470 --> 00:49:00.560
that have said they do still
value the big personality

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:01.700
umpire who can--

00:49:01.700 --> 00:49:03.890
I mean, Joe West, and I
pick on him all the time.

00:49:03.890 --> 00:49:07.457
But if there's a real
scrum on the field,

00:49:07.457 --> 00:49:09.290
he's a good person to
have out there for it.

00:49:09.290 --> 00:49:11.000
If there's actual
conflict, that's

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:12.680
where I think he really excels.

00:49:12.680 --> 00:49:14.875
And that is something you want.

00:49:14.875 --> 00:49:16.000
We don't want to be hockey.

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:18.170
We don't want fights to be
a huge part of the sport.

00:49:18.170 --> 00:49:21.870
Well, then, you probably do want
some umpires who can do that.

00:49:21.870 --> 00:49:24.305
I would argue that now
you've split the job, though.

00:49:24.305 --> 00:49:26.180
Somebody who's good at
that isn't necessarily

00:49:26.180 --> 00:49:28.727
going to be good at
ball-strike accuracy.

00:49:28.727 --> 00:49:31.310
Maybe that means Joe West should
always be a first base umpire

00:49:31.310 --> 00:49:32.840
and should never be
behind the plate.

00:49:32.840 --> 00:49:33.620
I'd be OK with that.

00:49:33.620 --> 00:49:34.880
I don't know if
the umpires would.

00:49:34.880 --> 00:49:36.505
But maybe that means
splitting the job.

00:49:36.505 --> 00:49:37.957
We want different
kinds of umpires

00:49:37.957 --> 00:49:40.040
so that we've got different
skill sets represented

00:49:40.040 --> 00:49:42.623
in the four spots, four people,
or in the post-season, the six

00:49:42.623 --> 00:49:44.600
people on the field.

00:49:44.600 --> 00:49:47.060
AUDIENCE: Have you ever
watched a national broadcast

00:49:47.060 --> 00:49:49.240
on ESPN or Fox?

00:49:49.240 --> 00:49:50.300
They're so bad.

00:49:50.300 --> 00:49:52.215
Why can't they get this right?

00:49:52.215 --> 00:49:53.840
KEITH LAW: I use the
mute button a lot.

00:49:53.840 --> 00:49:58.880
And that's not specific to ESPN,
or to Fox, or to anyone else.

00:49:58.880 --> 00:50:02.100
One problem I have also
is I know these players.

00:50:02.100 --> 00:50:03.670
I know a lot about the players.

00:50:03.670 --> 00:50:07.430
Often, you're not telling me
anything I don't already know.

00:50:07.430 --> 00:50:10.010
Or you're telling me
something I know isn't true.

00:50:10.010 --> 00:50:11.960
That drives me up the wall.

00:50:11.960 --> 00:50:16.160
And I don't want to start
talking back to the iPad

00:50:16.160 --> 00:50:18.440
because now I've got a
wife and a daughter who

00:50:18.440 --> 00:50:21.110
will both point out to me that
that's not really appropriate.

00:50:23.960 --> 00:50:28.790
I will say it's frickin
hard to do those things.

00:50:28.790 --> 00:50:30.650
This came up at one
of the recent signings

00:50:30.650 --> 00:50:32.600
I did around the book too.

00:50:32.600 --> 00:50:36.116
When you're trying to do color
commentary-- so I did a game--

00:50:36.116 --> 00:50:38.490
they had me do a whole game
in spring training this year,

00:50:38.490 --> 00:50:38.840
which is good.

00:50:38.840 --> 00:50:41.215
Much better than dropping in
for two, three innings where

00:50:41.215 --> 00:50:44.120
you barely have time to say hi.

00:50:44.120 --> 00:50:46.670
I got to give a lot of
content, but you can't educate.

00:50:46.670 --> 00:50:47.657
You get no opportunity.

00:50:47.657 --> 00:50:49.490
If I wanted to talk
weighted on-base average

00:50:49.490 --> 00:50:54.270
in the middle of a game, you
have 10, 15 seconds, maybe,

00:50:54.270 --> 00:50:55.190
to get something in.

00:50:55.190 --> 00:50:57.410
You can't explain concepts.

00:50:57.410 --> 00:50:59.750
You have to talk details.

00:50:59.750 --> 00:51:01.690
You have to talk about
what just happened,

00:51:01.690 --> 00:51:03.190
and give something
very pithy, which

00:51:03.190 --> 00:51:05.690
sometimes the pithy
explanation is not necessarily

00:51:05.690 --> 00:51:07.130
the right explanation.

00:51:07.130 --> 00:51:10.610
And if you start
rambling, there's

00:51:10.610 --> 00:51:12.112
a voice in your ear saying wrap.

00:51:12.112 --> 00:51:14.570
We got to go to commercial,
the next hitter's up, whatever.

00:51:14.570 --> 00:51:16.046
Or I'm very conscious of it.

00:51:16.046 --> 00:51:17.920
I see, all right, there's
a ball in play now.

00:51:17.920 --> 00:51:19.400
I have to stop talking.

00:51:19.400 --> 00:51:20.300
That's really hard.

00:51:20.300 --> 00:51:22.508
Whereas in a studio show,
you have a little more room

00:51:22.508 --> 00:51:23.930
to breathe.

00:51:23.930 --> 00:51:26.180
And then you can choreograph
everything from the start

00:51:26.180 --> 00:51:28.730
too and say, the
B block tonight,

00:51:28.730 --> 00:51:30.740
we're going to talk
about prospects.

00:51:30.740 --> 00:51:32.900
We're going to talk
about sabermetrics.

00:51:32.900 --> 00:51:34.460
We're going to
introduce one concept

00:51:34.460 --> 00:51:36.500
and spend a couple
of minutes on it.

00:51:36.500 --> 00:51:37.940
It's hard to figure
out how to do

00:51:37.940 --> 00:51:40.742
that in a game when you know
your main job is to just talk

00:51:40.742 --> 00:51:42.200
about what's
happening on the field

00:51:42.200 --> 00:51:44.366
and give people the basic
information that they need

00:51:44.366 --> 00:51:47.990
to understand what's in front
of them, which still doesn't

00:51:47.990 --> 00:51:50.150
excuse hey, he's
a clutch hitter.

00:51:50.150 --> 00:51:51.690
Hey, it's a big RBI spot.

00:51:51.690 --> 00:51:54.120
He smells that RBI
on second base.

00:51:54.120 --> 00:51:59.056
It's like, you could probably
skip that and we'd all be OK.

00:51:59.056 --> 00:52:01.384
AUDIENCE: Keith, you have a
lot of eclectic interests.

00:52:01.384 --> 00:52:03.800
And you mentioned that you
love learning about, basically,

00:52:03.800 --> 00:52:05.250
everything getting more data.

00:52:05.250 --> 00:52:07.190
So other than baseball,
what's something

00:52:07.190 --> 00:52:09.680
in either your personal
life or out in society where

00:52:09.680 --> 00:52:12.650
you would just love more data?

00:52:12.650 --> 00:52:16.610
KEITH LAW: Oh, that's
a really good question.

00:52:16.610 --> 00:52:18.200
Because when I
think of learning,

00:52:18.200 --> 00:52:21.475
I decide when I started
learning to cook 20 years ago,

00:52:21.475 --> 00:52:22.490
it wasn't really data.

00:52:22.490 --> 00:52:24.680
But I was looking
for people who took

00:52:24.680 --> 00:52:25.820
a more scientific approach.

00:52:25.820 --> 00:52:31.070
So it was Alton Brown, now
Kenji Lopez-Alt where not just

00:52:31.070 --> 00:52:33.440
their recipes but their
entire style of talking

00:52:33.440 --> 00:52:35.540
about something
is driven by data.

00:52:35.540 --> 00:52:37.580
Driven by, in their
cases, experimentation

00:52:37.580 --> 00:52:40.790
or understanding the
science behind cooking

00:52:40.790 --> 00:52:42.990
so that it works every time.

00:52:42.990 --> 00:52:45.060
You get it right the first time.

00:52:45.060 --> 00:52:48.230
That's the kind of thing I
like, regardless of what it is.

00:52:48.230 --> 00:52:51.140
When I'm-- when it's--

00:52:51.140 --> 00:52:53.360
even when I write
about books or movies,

00:52:53.360 --> 00:52:55.850
I'm nobody's critic
or expert on this.

00:52:55.850 --> 00:52:56.960
I just read a lot.

00:52:56.960 --> 00:52:59.427
And so I write a lot.

00:52:59.427 --> 00:53:01.010
But you'll notice a
lot of my reviews,

00:53:01.010 --> 00:53:02.600
they sort of follow
certain patterns.

00:53:02.600 --> 00:53:06.380
There's certain things that
I'm specifically looking for.

00:53:06.380 --> 00:53:09.997
I kind of think more
methodically about anything

00:53:09.997 --> 00:53:12.080
that I'm doing when I'm
talking about board games,

00:53:12.080 --> 00:53:15.560
or talking about art and
anything in the arts,

00:53:15.560 --> 00:53:17.330
or I'm talking about cooking.

00:53:17.330 --> 00:53:21.460
I'm always trying to break down
what are the criteria here.

00:53:21.460 --> 00:53:22.970
Maybe what are the criteria--

00:53:22.970 --> 00:53:24.490
hey, I liked playing that game.

00:53:24.490 --> 00:53:25.990
Well, what are the
specific criteria

00:53:25.990 --> 00:53:29.260
that made me like that game,
to get behind my own thinking?

00:53:29.260 --> 00:53:31.010
So that's probably
not an exact answer

00:53:31.010 --> 00:53:33.889
to your question because I'm not
thinking of an interest of mine

00:53:33.889 --> 00:53:36.180
where I could necessarily
say I want more data on that.

00:53:36.180 --> 00:53:40.280
But it's the whole sort of
more rational, analytical way

00:53:40.280 --> 00:53:43.056
of breaking down my
thinking on everything.

00:53:43.056 --> 00:53:44.930
Because then I can also
say, well, all right,

00:53:44.930 --> 00:53:46.820
now I know what I like,
or now I know what worked.

00:53:46.820 --> 00:53:48.230
Hey, I can go make
my own recipe.

00:53:48.230 --> 00:53:50.300
Hey, I can go figure out
what board game to play

00:53:50.300 --> 00:53:51.640
next, what book to read next.

00:53:51.640 --> 00:53:53.584
Well, I know these are
three or four things

00:53:53.584 --> 00:53:55.250
that I've specifically
liked in the past

00:53:55.250 --> 00:53:58.970
and then target what I'm
looking for next to meet

00:53:58.970 --> 00:54:02.546
those criteria that I've
identified for myself.

00:54:02.546 --> 00:54:05.540
MATT TEPER: On combining
the love of cooking

00:54:05.540 --> 00:54:07.920
and the love of baseball,
I put out a call

00:54:07.920 --> 00:54:09.705
to some folks, baseball
fans at Google.

00:54:09.705 --> 00:54:11.330
And one of the
questions that came back

00:54:11.330 --> 00:54:13.700
was, with your love
of both things,

00:54:13.700 --> 00:54:18.030
what stadium has the best food?

00:54:18.030 --> 00:54:21.165
KEITH LAW: Citi
Field has great food.

00:54:21.165 --> 00:54:22.790
They're mostly Danny
Meyer restaurants.

00:54:22.790 --> 00:54:25.577
So it's like a Shake
Shack, Blue Smoke.

00:54:25.577 --> 00:54:27.410
I'm trying to think of
where else I've been.

00:54:27.410 --> 00:54:29.910
I've not been to the new Atlanta
stadium, but Hugh Acheson--

00:54:29.910 --> 00:54:32.520
who I think did one
of these talks--

00:54:32.520 --> 00:54:36.020
has a sausage stand there, which
will be the place I go eat.

00:54:36.020 --> 00:54:36.860
Target Field.

00:54:36.860 --> 00:54:39.200
Actually, Target Field,
that's the first one I've

00:54:39.200 --> 00:54:43.190
been to where they seem to get a
diverse selection of local food

00:54:43.190 --> 00:54:44.840
vendors because--

00:54:44.840 --> 00:54:46.466
the problem with
stadium food and why

00:54:46.466 --> 00:54:47.840
I don't eat a lot
of stadium food

00:54:47.840 --> 00:54:52.190
is it's either the Aramark
type garbage stadium food,

00:54:52.190 --> 00:54:53.630
or it's national chains.

00:54:53.630 --> 00:54:56.150
Like, I don't need Panda
Express at a stadium.

00:54:56.150 --> 00:54:58.910
If I wanted to eat bad,
imitation Chinese food,

00:54:58.910 --> 00:55:01.820
I can get that on
any corner, right?

00:55:01.820 --> 00:55:02.942
Like, I'll pay more.

00:55:02.942 --> 00:55:03.650
I'm at a stadium.

00:55:03.650 --> 00:55:05.369
I'm expecting I'm
going to pay more.

00:55:05.369 --> 00:55:06.410
Give me a better product.

00:55:06.410 --> 00:55:06.710
MATT TEPER: Yeah.

00:55:06.710 --> 00:55:08.210
KEITH LAW: And when
the Futures Game

00:55:08.210 --> 00:55:10.110
was at Target Field a
couple of years ago,

00:55:10.110 --> 00:55:13.025
I was floored by how many
different local restaurants.

00:55:13.025 --> 00:55:16.450
Andrew Zimmern's got a--
the "Bizarre Foods" guy--

00:55:16.450 --> 00:55:18.200
he's got at least one
food stand in there.

00:55:18.200 --> 00:55:20.939
The Butcher and Boar, which is
a high-end restaurant there,

00:55:20.939 --> 00:55:22.730
has a food stand where
it's just two items,

00:55:22.730 --> 00:55:26.360
but it's this incredibly
high-quality food

00:55:26.360 --> 00:55:27.810
to be getting at a stadium.

00:55:27.810 --> 00:55:30.309
And especially now with the
high price point of Major League

00:55:30.309 --> 00:55:32.300
tickets, it just makes
sense that if you're

00:55:32.300 --> 00:55:33.980
going to ask them to
pay $14 for a beer,

00:55:33.980 --> 00:55:35.780
you might as well
actually provide them

00:55:35.780 --> 00:55:38.320
with better food at
that same price point.

00:55:38.320 --> 00:55:39.327
MATT TEPER: Yeah.

00:55:39.327 --> 00:55:40.410
One last question from me.

00:55:40.410 --> 00:55:40.960
KEITH LAW: Yeah.

00:55:40.960 --> 00:55:42.230
MATT TEPER: I have
two little girls.

00:55:42.230 --> 00:55:43.105
We've discussed that.

00:55:43.105 --> 00:55:45.010
You have a little girl.

00:55:45.010 --> 00:55:47.396
Will a woman ever play
Major League Baseball?

00:55:47.396 --> 00:55:48.560
KEITH LAW: Ever?

00:55:48.560 --> 00:55:49.520
Yeah, probably.

00:55:49.520 --> 00:55:50.801
It'll be a long time.

00:55:50.801 --> 00:55:51.800
It would be a long time.

00:55:51.800 --> 00:55:55.872
I mean, there are
cultural factors.

00:55:55.872 --> 00:55:57.830
They're just discouraged
from playing baseball.

00:55:57.830 --> 00:55:59.000
Girls play softball, right?

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:03.260
So even if someone shows
the ability, most of them

00:56:03.260 --> 00:56:06.950
are going to get steered
off into the wrong sport.

00:56:06.950 --> 00:56:10.820
And you asked earlier
about biases around size.

00:56:10.820 --> 00:56:12.674
I mean, that's
always going to hurt.

00:56:12.674 --> 00:56:14.840
It's going to have to be a
woman who's exceptionally

00:56:14.840 --> 00:56:17.450
tall, exceptionally strong.

00:56:17.450 --> 00:56:19.069
She's going to have to be more.

00:56:19.069 --> 00:56:21.110
The standards that we
would hold male players to,

00:56:21.110 --> 00:56:23.870
the woman is going to have to
exceed all of those standards

00:56:23.870 --> 00:56:26.810
by a fairly large margin
before she's taken seriously

00:56:26.810 --> 00:56:29.300
enough by the industry.

00:56:29.300 --> 00:56:32.060
And that's not even
just gender bias.

00:56:32.060 --> 00:56:36.590
It's just the way baseball's
always treated its outliers.

00:56:36.590 --> 00:56:39.710
It was the reluctance to let--

00:56:39.710 --> 00:56:42.010
not to let but to pay.

00:56:42.010 --> 00:56:45.560
Like, when Hideo Nomo came over,
it's like, that'll never work.

00:56:45.560 --> 00:56:46.980
Japanese got a weird delivery.

00:56:46.980 --> 00:56:50.420
That's never gonna-- I mean,
Japanese pitchers have been OK,

00:56:50.420 --> 00:56:50.920
right?

00:56:50.920 --> 00:56:52.230
We've had a few
pretty good ones.

00:56:52.230 --> 00:56:54.271
But there was a huge bias
because that was other.

00:56:54.271 --> 00:56:57.410
That's just not how we do
things because we've always

00:56:57.410 --> 00:56:59.870
had a hard time
fitting players who

00:56:59.870 --> 00:57:03.620
don't fit our archetypes
into traditional evaluation.

00:57:03.620 --> 00:57:04.402
Data is blind.

00:57:04.402 --> 00:57:06.110
So we don't know what
the guy looks like.

00:57:06.110 --> 00:57:07.070
We don't know what
the delivery is like.

00:57:07.070 --> 00:57:08.180
We don't know how
hard he's throwing.

00:57:08.180 --> 00:57:09.846
We just know he's
missing a lot of bats.

00:57:09.846 --> 00:57:10.625
MATT TEPER: Yeah.

00:57:10.625 --> 00:57:12.500
KEITH LAW: Yeah, thank you guys.

00:57:12.500 --> 00:57:14.950
[APPLAUSE]

